{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505075"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:25:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:25:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2402"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2402"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.26,0.21,0.03,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47216"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2402"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31937"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"8840"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10006"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47216"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old blacksmith presents to his general practitioner with increasing pain, tearing, and worsening vision in his right eye. This started after he had been striking a metal object with a metal chisel and felt something strike his right eye. He was not wearing safety glasses. On examination, the right conjunctiva is injected. On fluorescein dye instillment, a flow of aqueous humour as a waterfall appearance is seen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management in the emergency department?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Application of eye shield and administration of topical antibiotics","Application of eye patch and gentle removal of intra-ocular foreign body","Application of eye shield and administration of antiemetics and oral antibiotics","Topical anaesthetic (amethocaine) and review the following day","Application of eye shield and administration of topical antibiotics and cycloplegic medication"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a positive Seidel test as indicated by the \u0027waterfall\u0027 appearance of aqueous humour on fluorescein dye instillment. This indicates globe perforation and necessitates urgent ophthalmological referral and hospital admission for removal of the intraocular foreign body (IOFB) and globe repair. A ruptured globe is at risk of further diffuse injury and haemorrhagic choroidal and retinal detachment.  The appropriate imaging prior to surgery would be a CT scan of the orbit in order to localise the IOFB. An MRI must not be done as the IOFB is likely to be ferrous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate management in the emergency department would be \u003Cstrong\u003Eapplication of an eye shield and administration of antiemetics and oral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E. An eye shield should always be placed over the eye to reduce any risk of herniation of ocular contents through the rupture by preventing inadvertent pressure or digital manipulation of the eye. The purpose of antiemetics is to reduce the risk of increased intra-ocular pressure. Prophylactic antibiotic treatment is necessary to prevent endophthalmitis, which is a common complication following globe perforation.  Tetanus status must also be attained if prophylaxis is required.  Topical or local anaesthesia is difficult as some anaesthetic medications can increase intraocular pressure and must be discussed with an Ophthalmology Consultant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplication of eye shield and administration of topical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. An eye shield should be placed immediately but any sort of topical medication is strongly contraindicated. Therefore, the option of \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical anaesthetic (amethocaine) and review the following day\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eapplication of eye shield and administration of topical antibiotics and cycloplegic medication\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplication of an eye patch and gentle removal of the intra-ocular foreign body\u003C/strong\u003E is strongly contraindicated in management of globe perforation. Any foreign bodies should not be removed except in an operative setting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The mainstay of pre-operative management for globe rupture is immediate placement of an eye shield, along with oral antiemetic and antibiotic treatment"],"references":["Camodeca AJ, Anderson EP. Corneal Foreign Body. [Updated 2020 Aug 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 January. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK536977/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31937"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2402"}},"stemMedia"